# Python
__pycache__/
*.py[cod]
.venv/
build/
*.egg-info/

# NOTE: `dist/` is deliberately NOT ignored, which is unusual for a Python project and is
# the whole point. `dist/` is not a build artifact here — it is THE PUBLISHED FEED, and it
# is the product: index.html, feed.xml, changes.json, sources.json, and a feed per
# jurisdiction. Committing it means the site can be served by GitHub Pages, by any static
# host, or by `python -m http.server` out of a clean clone, with **no build step and no CI
# run**. That matters concretely: this account has an Actions spending limit, and a feed
# that only exists after somebody else's billing system agrees to run a workflow is a feed
# that does not exist. It also means a reviewer can see, in the diff, exactly what changed
# in the published bytes before it reaches an org that acts on them.
#
# The one thing that must never appear in it is an unreviewed record — which is not a
# gitignore's job to enforce, and is enforced by `make no-unreviewed-in-feed` instead.

# Tooling
.pytest_cache/
.mypy_cache/
.ruff_cache/
.coverage
coverage.xml
htmlcov/

# The snapshot store: fetched government pages, regenerable, and not something to
# commit (it grows without bound in a git history and adds nothing a reviewer needs).
var/
